<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Under a system of fractional reserve banking, the money multiplier is reduced when:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Banks reduce their excess reserves</option>
            <option letter="b">The required reserve ratio decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">The public holds less currency relative to deposits</option>
            <option letter="d">The currency drain ratio increases</option>
        </options>
        <answer>d</answer>
        <explanation>An increase in the currency drain ratio (the ratio of currency to deposits held by the public) reduces the money multiplier by decreasing the amount of deposits available for lending.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Time inconsistency in monetary policy refers to:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">The lag between policy changes and their effects</option>
            <option letter="b">The tendency to deviate from announced low-inflation policies</option>
            <option letter="c">Changes in the velocity of money</option>
            <option letter="d">Seasonal adjustments in the money supply</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Time inconsistency occurs when policymakers have an incentive to deviate from previously announced low-inflation policies once expectations are set.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>The twin deficits hypothesis suggests that:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Budget deficits cause trade deficits</option>
            <option letter="b">Trade deficits cause budget deficits</option>
            <option letter="c">Both deficits are caused by high interest rates</option>
            <option letter="d">The deficits are unrelated</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The twin deficits hypothesis argues that government budget deficits lead to trade deficits by increasing national borrowing and attracting foreign capital inflows.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>In the efficiency wage theory, unemployment results from:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Minimum wage laws</option>
            <option letter="b">Firms paying above-market wages</option>
            <option letter="c">Labor unions</option>
            <option letter="d">Cyclical factors</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Efficiency wage theory suggests firms deliberately pay above-market wages to increase productivity and reduce turnover, resulting in unemployment as wages remain above market-clearing levels.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
